{"title_page": "Charles Mann (songwriter)", "text_new": "{{other people||Charles Mann (disambiguation){{!}}Charles Mann}}\n'''Charles Mann''' (1949\u20131991), also named Charles M. Mann, was an [[United States|American]] [[R&B]] songwriter, [[soul music|soul]] singer, [[record producer]] and musician. He worked during the 1970s into the [[Philadelphia soul|Philly Sound]] world. He should not be confused with its namesake, the [[swamp pop]] singer [[Charles Mann (singer)|Charles Mann]] born in 1944.<ref group=note>Several websites dedicated to music confuse these two people or their date of birth.</ref>\n\n==Life and career==\nCharles M. Mann was born on December 29, 1949 in [[Atlanta]], [[Georgia (U.S. state)|Georgia]].<ref>{{cite web| url=https://www.imdb.com/name/nm2379095/bio| title=Charles Mann| website=IMDb| accessdate=2014-11-17}}</ref> He built up a reputation as a writer and performer in the Atlanta area, which allowed him to be spotted by Jay Lasker, then president of [[ABC Records]], who signed him for the label at the beginning of 1973.<ref>''[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]'', March 2, 1973, p. 26.</ref>\n\nAs a songwriter, often in partnership with [[Dave Crawford (musician)|Dave Crawford]], he wrote and composed for artists such as [[B.B. King]], [[Mighty Clouds of Joy|The Mighty Clouds of Joy]] and [[Nature's Gift]]. He obtained five hits in the R&B Top 100, including one hit in the Top 10 (''I Like to Live the Love'' by [[B.B. King]] in 1973).<ref>{{cite web|\nurl=http://www.musicvf.com/songs.php?page=artist&artist=Charles+Mann&tab=songaswriterchartstab| title=Songs written by Charles Mann| website=MusicVF.com| accessdate=2014-11-11}}</ref>\n\nAs a solo singer, he had a minor hit in 1973 with the song '\"It's All Over\", a track from his Philadelphia-recorded album ''Say You Love Me Too''. Produced by Dave Crawford, the title track reached #36 on the Billboard R&B chart.\n\nFrom 1977, he worked as a writer, arranger and producer for two labels owned by a company based in [[Chapel Hill, North Carolina]], which had  to stop its activities in 1980 for illegally marketing bootleg recordings.<ref>''[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]'', August 23, 1980, p. 56.</ref>\n\nHe later signed for Crawford's own small Los Angeles based label, LA Records and released \"Shonuff No Funny Stuff Love\", in 1981.\n\nCharles M. Mann died on April 24, 1991 in [[Atlanta]] ([[Fulton County, Georgia|Fulton County]]), [[Georgia (U.S. state)|Georgia]].<ref>{{cite web| url=https://familysearch.org/ark:/61903/1:1:V4S7-X9Y| title=Georgia Death Index| website=FamilySearch| accessdate=2015-10-11}}</ref>\n\n== Discography ==\n\n=== Performer <small>(as ''Charles Mann'')</small> ===\n\n==== Singles ====\n* 1973 : \"Do It Again\" / \"It's All Over\"\n* 1973 : \"Say You Love Me Too\" / \"I Can Feel It\" <small>(ABC 13347)</small>\n* 1973 : \"It's All Over\" / \"Very Lonely\" <small>(ABC 11384)</small>\n* 1974 : \"Got To Let You Know\" / \"Loving You Is Changing Me\" <small>(ABC 11434)</small>\n* 1981 : \"Shonuff No Funny Stuff Love\" / \"Shonuff No Funny Stuff Love (instrumental)\" <small>(LA Records LA 0070 7)</small>\n\n==== Albums ====\n* 1973 : ''Say You Love Me Too'' <small>(ABC Records ABCX 786)</small>\n\n=== Producer <small>(as ''Charles M. Mann'')</small> ===\n* 1977 : The Original Marauders - \"Now Your Mouth Cries Wolf - A Tribute To Bob Dylan\" (LP, <small>Pied Piper Records 7902</small>)\n* 1977 : Blue Heaven - \"After The Deluge - A Tribute To Jackson Browne\" (LP, <small>Pied Piper Records 7905</small>)\n* 1977 : The Great Imposters - \"Dollars In Drag - A Tribute To David Bowie\" (LP, <small>Pied  Piper Records 7907</small>)\n* 1977 : The Great Imposters - \"20/20 Hindsight - A Tribute To Nazz\" (LP, <small>Pied Piper Records 7908</small>)\n* 1978 : The Blazers - \"Store Bought\" (LP, <small>Cream Of The Crop Records 7956</small>)<ref>{{cite web|\nurl=http://www.discogs.com/artist/2924630-Charles-M-Mann| title=Charles M. Mann| website=Discogs| accessdate=2015-10-11}}</ref>\n* 1979 : Robert, Rory and Ricky (LP, <small>Cream Of The Crop Records 7957</small>)<ref>''[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]'', January 13, 1979, p. 80.</ref>\n\n==Notes==\n{{reflist|group=note}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.discogs.com/artist/386303-Charles-Mann Charles Mann at Discogs.com]\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Mann, Charles (songwriter)}}\n[[Category:American male writers]]\n[[Category:American soul singers]]\n[[Category:Musicians from Atlanta]]\n[[Category:1949 births]]\n[[Category:1991 deaths]]\n[[Category:20th-century American singers]]\n[[Category:Songwriters from Georgia (U.S. state)]]\n", "text_old": "{{other people||Charles Mann (disambiguation){{!}}Charles Mann}}\n'''Charles Mann''' (1949\u20131991), also named Charles M. Mann, was an [[United States|American]] [[R&B]] songwriter, [[soul music|soul]] singer, [[record producer]] and musician. He worked during the 1970s into the [[Philadelphia soul|Philly Sound]] world. He should not be confused with its namesake, the [[swamp pop]] singer [[Charles Mann (singer)|Charles Mann]] born in 1944.<ref group=note>Several websites dedicated to music confuse these two people or their date of birth.</ref>\n\n==Life and career==\nCharles M. Mann was born on December 29, 1949 in [[Atlanta]], [[Georgia (U.S. state)|Georgia]].<ref>{{cite web| url=https://www.imdb.com/name/nm2379095/bio| title=Charles Mann| website=IMDb| accessdate=2014-11-17}}</ref> He built up a reputation as a writer and performer in the Atlanta area, which allowed him to be spotted by Jay Lasker, then president of [[ABC Records]], who signed him for the label at the beginning of 1973.<ref>''[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]'', March 2, 1973, p. 26.</ref>\n\nAs a songwriter, often in partnership with [[Dave Crawford (musician)|Dave Crawford]], he wrote and composed for artists such as [[B.B. King]], [[Mighty Clouds of Joy|The Mighty Clouds of Joy]] and [[Nature's Gift]]. He obtained five hits in the R&B Top 100, including one hit in the Top 10 (''I Like to Live the Love'' by [[B.B. King]] in 1973).<ref>{{cite web|\nurl=http://www.musicvf.com/songs.php?page=artist&artist=Charles+Mann&tab=songaswriterchartstab| title=Songs written by Charles Mann| website=MusicVF.com| accessdate=2014-11-11}}</ref>\n\nAs a solo singer, he had a minor hit in 1973 with the song '\"It's All Over\", a track from his Philadelphia-recorded album ''Say You Love Me Too''. Produced by Dave Crawford, the title track reached #36 on the Billboard R&B chart.\n\nFrom 1977, he worked as a writer, arranger and producer for two labels owned by a company based in [[Chapel Hill, North Carolina]], which had  to stop its activities in 1980 for illegally marketing bootleg recordings.<ref>''[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]'', August 23, 1980, p. 56.</ref>\n\nHe later signed for Crawford's own small Los Angeles based label, LA Records and released \"Shonuff No Funny Stuff Love\", in 1981.\n\nCharles M. Mann died on April 24, 1991 in [[Atlanta]] ([[Fulton County, Georgia|Fulton County]]), [[Georgia (U.S. state)|Georgia]].<ref>{{cite web| url=https://familysearch.org/ark:/61903/1:1:V4S7-X9Y| title=Georgia Death Index| website=FamilySearch| accessdate=2015-10-11}}</ref>\n\n== Discography ==\n\n=== Performer <small>(as ''Charles Mann'')</small> ===\n\n==== Singles ====\n* 1973 : \"Do It Again\" / \"It's All Over\"\n* 1973 : \"Say You Love Me Too\" / \"I Can Feel It\" <small>(ABC 13347)</small>\n* 1973 : \"It's All Over\" / \"Very Lonely\" <small>(ABC 11384)</small>\n* 1974 : \"Got To Let You Know\" / \"Loving You Is Changing Me\" <small>(ABC 11434)</small>\n* 1981 : \"Shonuff No Funny Stuff Love\" / \"Shonuff No Funny Stuff Love (instrumental)\" <small>(LA Records LA 0070 7)</small>\n\n==== Albums ====\n* 1973 : ''Say You Love Me Too'' <small>(ABC Records ABCX 786)</small>\n\n=== Producer <small>(as ''Charles M. Mann'')</small> ===\n* 1977 : The Original 